comments.message:
The C standard requires the same behaviour for both

    char buffer[PATH_MAX] = "";

and 

    char buffer[PATH_MAX] = {0};

See C99 6.7.8.14 and 6.7.8.21.

Using argv[0] is an okay fallback for systems where we don't know any other way of getting the self exe.

On Linux:

  char self[PATH_MAX] = { 0 };
  int nchar = readlink("/proc/self/exe", self, sizeof self);

Then check for nchar being negative, or >= sizeof self.

One problem with argv[0] is that if the program is found using a PATH search (the case when the user has sourced the toolchain script), then argv[0] will just be the name of the program like "mkdiff", and not a path name. Then if we do a realpath() on this string, realpath will look for it in the current directory and return NULL when it doesn't find it. Then we pass NULL into dirname.

This comment may be kind of off topic to the patch, sorry.

The coding choice creates a bit of confusion in the code. Because argc is the argument count including the program name. So now if we have four arguments (including the program name), argvPtr will point to the first of three remaining arguments, yet iargc is 4.

Since we are editing various lines where iargc is checked, this would be a good opportunity to fix this:

   char **argvPtr = argv + 1;
   int iargc = argc - 1;

This won't never happen, because we checked that argvPtr points to the first of three more arguments, the third of which becomes outPathPtr. In argv[] there  is a null pointer only after the last argument (argv[argc] == NULL). So if all our argument processing is correct, we don't have to check this.

If we are worried about the argvPtr and iargc manipulations not being correct somewhere, we can do something like this:

  // sanity check argument extraction movements
  if (argvPtr - argv != argc - iargv) {
    fprintf(stderr, "internal error in argument handling\n");
    abort();
  }

This is an unusual way to initialize a string. Barring any C-language peculiarities, I would do e.g.
src_file_path[0] = '\0';
This initializes it to an empty string. Is this what Klocwork is complaining about?
